properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and blowing snow are expected. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm possible. Locations: Rigolet to Black Tickle. Time span: Saturday evening until early Sunday morning. Remarks: After a brief period of snow and rain tonight, conditions will improve for most of Saturday. However, snow is expected to develop again on Saturday evening with strong northwesterly winds. Blowing snow advisories may also be required. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant high-elevation snowfall is expected. Total snowfall: near 5 cm, except 15 to 25 cm over higher terrain. Time span: this evening until Saturday night. Locations: Bay St. George to Hawke's Bay. Remarks: Rain will persist this evening over coastal areas while snow will persist over the Long Range Mountains. Precipitation will transition to flurries over all areas by Saturday morning. Flurries will then continue through Saturday with possible snow squalls, before gradually easing Saturday night. Anyone using the Viking Trail through Gros Morne National Park or high-elevation backcountry trails should be prepared for winter travel conditions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For The Roseau River From Gardenton To Stuartburn
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Roseau River from Gardenton to Stuartburn due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-11-16T16:30:00-06:00

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Persistent snow squalls are expected to develop. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Strong and cold northwest winds blowing over relatively warm Gulf of St. Lawrence waters will make conditions favourable for the development of snow squalls on Saturday. Conditions are expected to persist until Sunday morning as a ridge of high pressure moves over the region. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. Heavy rain is expected for the coastal sections of the Central Coast and West Vancouver Island. An atmospheric river will take aim at Vancouver Island and the Central Coast beginning early Saturday morning delivering heavy rain and mild conditions until mid-day Sunday. Rainfall amounts of 100 to 120 mm are expected by Sunday morning for the aforementioned regions. Given the tropical origin of the atmospheric river, freezing levels will be on the rise upwards of 3000 metres for the South Coast and close to 2500 metres for the North Coast. The mild air will result in rain at almost all elevations. High runoff and rising river levels are likely through the weekend. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2019-11-16T16:07:39-00:00

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. An area of freezing rain is tracking through east central Alberta and northwestern Saskatchewan. This area is expected to continue to track eastward overnight tonight and move out of the area after midnight. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. Heavy rain is expected for the inland sections of the north and central coasts, the Sunshine Coast and Howe Sound. An atmospheric river will take aim at North Vancouver Island and the Central Coast beginning early Saturday morning delivering heavy rain and mild conditions until mid-day Sunday. Rainfall amounts of 50 to 70 mm are expected by Sunday morning for the aforementioned regions. Given the tropical origin of the atmospheric river, freezing levels will be on the rise upwards of 3000 metres for the South Coast and close to 2500 metres for the North Coast. The mild air will result in rain at almost all elevations. High runoff and rising river levels are likely through the weekend. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: 100 km/h. Locations: Channel-Port aux Basques and vicinity. Time span: Saturday afternoon until Saturday evening. Remarks: A period of strong northwesterly winds is expected to develop on Saturday, with the highest gusts likely to occur along exposed areas of the coast. ### Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A vigorous frontal system will approach Haida Gwaii tonight. Southeast winds will increase to 90 km/h gusting to 110 overnight as the front approaches. The winds will become southwesterly and ease Saturday near noon. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
